body:
I am wondering how I can show that the solution ( $P$ ) to the following matrix differential equation $$\begin{align}
\dot{P}(t) &= -A^{\top}P - PA + PBR^{-1}B^{\top}P - Q \\[3mm]
P(t_{1}) &= S
\end{align}$$ where $$\begin{align}
A = \begin{bmatrix}-4&0\\0&0\end{bmatrix},\quad B = \begin{bmatrix}2\\-2\end{bmatrix},\quad Q = \begin{bmatrix}4&4\\4&4\end{bmatrix},\quad S = \begin{bmatrix}0&0\\0&0\end{bmatrix}\quad \text{and}\quad R= \begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{bmatrix},
\end{align}$$ is positive definite (i.e., $P > 0$ ) without solving the matrix differential equation. Is there some way we can see this, maybe by first rewriting the RHS? What are some useful properties one could use? For those of you unfamiliar with this equation, there actually exists a unique solution $P$ to this equation if $Q$ and $S$ are positive semidefinite and $R$ positive definite, which they all are in case. It is also true that the solution $P$ , in general, is positive semidefinite. I do not have the proof for this, unfortunately.
